I also think it's extremely important the context in which a child draws.

39:21.040 --> 39:27.560
Heidegger has a famous paper, George from the origin of the work of art in which he

39:27.560 --> 39:36.480
conceives of the work not as a drawing but as the work of the drawing, the process of

39:36.480 --> 39:37.480
the drawing.

39:37.480 --> 39:43.200
And I myself in my work am very interested in that, in the process by which the child

39:43.200 --> 39:44.200
draws.

39:44.200 --> 39:48.440
You give a child drawing implements.

39:48.440 --> 39:54.400
And you know in Darfur when there were all of the horrible genocide going on in Darfur,

39:54.400 --> 39:59.400
the human rights workers were interviewing the parents.

39:59.400 --> 40:01.360
The children were there.

40:01.360 --> 40:07.920
And just to keep the children busy and quiet, the front of the French workers gave the children

40:07.920 --> 40:10.040
some drawing materials.

40:10.040 --> 40:11.200
Children began to drop.

40:11.200 --> 40:13.160
They weren't told to do a drawing.

40:13.160 --> 40:15.480
They just drew.

40:15.480 --> 40:21.400
The drawings are stunning because the children drew the atrocities that were going on.

40:21.400 --> 40:26.480
Uninhibitedly they drew blood and death.

40:26.480 --> 40:28.920
And they even developed an iconography for it.

40:28.920 --> 40:34.720
So when you had a human being turned upside down, that was a dead person in the iconography

40:34.720 --> 40:38.800
that these children spontaneously evolved.

40:38.800 --> 40:42.440
But the children did the drawings without being told to do anything.

40:42.440 --> 40:43.440
We saw guns.

40:43.440 --> 40:49.360
We saw, I gave a lecture on this at the Sperdiss Institute in Chicago shortly after this.

40:49.360 --> 40:53.800
I got hold of this drawing.

40:53.800 --> 41:01.800
If you tell children, draw a boy or draw a girl, draw a human being, you are giving

41:01.800 --> 41:03.880
a task to the child.

41:03.880 --> 41:12.400
And part of what the child will do, I think, is to want to please the adult.

41:12.400 --> 41:16.840
In the same way that we have this problem with every kind of questionnaire that's given,

41:16.840 --> 41:24.840
where the person answering wants to please or do something appropriate or something acceptable.

41:24.840 --> 41:28.720
But I think that's very different from the child who gets something.

41:28.720 --> 41:31.160
And then we want to ask why.

41:31.160 --> 41:38.200
When you give a child drawing materials and the child starts to draw, why is the child

41:38.200 --> 41:39.200
drawing?

41:39.200 --> 41:41.640
What is the impetus for that?

41:41.640 --> 41:45.120
So in the literature, there are two schools of thought about that.

41:45.120 --> 41:50.120
The schools of thought are matching and marking.

41:50.120 --> 41:54.880
So you have scholars who say there's just a desire to make a mark.

41:54.880 --> 41:57.400
You know, kill or I was here.

41:57.400 --> 41:59.400
You make your mark.

41:59.400 --> 42:05.720
And then there's a school of thought that the idea is to represent something.

42:05.720 --> 42:09.600
Draw something that looks like something, that represents something.

42:09.600 --> 42:15.400
As we see, for example, in Lesco in the cave paintings.

42:15.400 --> 42:20.120
And there's a division about which of these impulses is primary.

42:20.120 --> 42:27.880
In the psychoanalytic literature, there's a brilliant paper by Ernst Chris, who's a great,

42:27.880 --> 42:31.720
not only a great psychoanalytic writer, but he was an art historian at the Kriśtus

42:31.720 --> 42:32.720
Dorsches Museum in Vienna.

42:32.720 --> 42:34.600
And it has this amazing paper.

42:34.600 --> 42:39.000
It's not in his book, Psychoanalytic Explorations in Art.

42:39.000 --> 42:40.000
It's not.

42:40.000 --> 42:42.320
It's in the psychoanalytic study, The Child, I think.

42:42.320 --> 42:46.560
And in this paper, he describes a little boy at the easel.

42:46.560 --> 42:50.200
I think it's a boy, I think, but it doesn't make, it could make absolutely no difference

42:50.200 --> 42:52.160
to you, a girl just as easily.

42:52.160 --> 42:59.760
And the child is taking paint and brush and making wonderful marks and just the pleasure

42:59.760 --> 43:04.960
of putting the paint on this paper is the impetus, impetus.

43:04.960 --> 43:15.200
And Chris describes it, and then at a certain point, the child looks at what's there.

43:15.200 --> 43:24.080
And the child takes a color and puts something on the page in response to what is actually

43:24.080 --> 43:25.080
there.

43:25.080 --> 43:30.000
And in that moment, Chris suggests this is the moment when art is born.

43:30.000 --> 43:36.000
This is the moment where you begin to have an artist because the artist isn't just enjoying

43:36.000 --> 43:40.120
the smearing and the fun of the materials.

43:40.120 --> 43:46.800
The artist is actually making what we're using ego functions of judgment and developing skill

43:46.800 --> 43:53.400
to try to make something that pleases him cognitively, intellectually, aesthetically.

43:53.400 --> 43:58.640
So I don't think we have to choose, but when we think about children's drawings, I think

43:58.640 --> 44:05.560
we may want to ask ourselves about these questions of marking and matching.

44:05.560 --> 44:12.440
The second point I want to make, which is another big, huge conflict in the literature

44:12.440 --> 44:20.960
on children's drawings, is the question which really bears on these two, both of your presentations.

44:20.960 --> 44:28.320
The presentation that you gave Nathan, where we see these children who are exile children

44:28.320 --> 44:35.560
coming to Israel from Ethiopia in a new land with all kinds of problems of immigration

44:35.560 --> 44:42.040
and so on, attachment which was then the perspective that you brought.

44:42.040 --> 44:47.600
Yeah, I call you Ted.

44:47.600 --> 44:52.320
Where you talked about the scientific, the universal kinds of issues.

44:52.320 --> 45:02.200
So there are certain scholars who say the children will draw because this is how it

45:02.200 --> 45:03.200
is.

45:03.200 --> 45:07.400
This is the biological necessity to do certain things.

45:07.400 --> 45:14.480
Other people will say absolutely not, but children are drawing its profoundly conditioned

45:14.480 --> 45:17.680
by the cultural context in which the child draws.

45:17.680 --> 45:25.920
And I see these two perspectives as, there's a lot of fighting in the literature about

45:25.920 --> 45:28.280
this, but I don't think we have to fight about it.

45:28.280 --> 45:35.680
I think we can simply see that it's a huge mistake to just talk about what's lighting

45:35.680 --> 45:38.600
up in the brain without understanding the culture.

45:38.600 --> 45:44.960
Ellen, I have a parallel comment about that that may be related to.

45:44.960 --> 45:50.600
That human beings, whatever culture they are, whatever language is spoken, speak a language

45:50.600 --> 45:56.160
and fairly competently by three years of age is a human issue.

45:56.160 --> 46:01.480
Whether you speak English or German depends on what your mother took, spoke to you.

46:01.480 --> 46:05.160
So that's a parallel notion.

46:05.160 --> 46:07.640
The capacity to do it is one thing.

46:07.640 --> 46:09.640
What you do and what its content is.

46:09.640 --> 46:22.280
It doesn't solve a third issue, which is the issue of why is it that the child takes so

46:22.280 --> 46:31.440
much longer to draw what the child can articulate, describe, and say.

46:31.440 --> 46:34.360
Once again, there are a lot of theories about this.

46:34.360 --> 46:41.720
A great root of Aernheim has a theory about this, but we know that every child by three

46:41.720 --> 46:49.360
can name every toe and every finger and so on, but the child will not draw that.

46:49.360 --> 46:56.640
I think that's probably a matter of maturation and biological integration.

46:56.640 --> 47:06.680
In fact, one of the questions that comes up, I showed you, the head end of the organism

47:06.680 --> 47:07.080
is highly put together in the beginning of life.

47:07.080 --> 47:11.440
Development goes from the head down, Cephalocore.

47:11.440 --> 47:16.720
The child doesn't even appreciate too stimuli, for example, if you touch a hand in the face,

47:16.720 --> 47:22.360
they won't appreciate the hand until they're pushing towards six.

47:22.360 --> 47:25.720
All of these are newly integrated aspects of it.

47:25.720 --> 47:29.320
They don't represent the middle of the body, you'll notice, but they represent the hands

47:29.320 --> 47:32.520
and the toes, which is just the way the brain is organized.

47:32.520 --> 47:39.400
If you look at the sensory strip, the thumb has a huge area of that brain compared to

47:39.400 --> 47:40.640
what the middle of the body.

47:40.640 --> 47:46.120
If you use something as simple as two-point discrimination on your finger, you can get

47:46.120 --> 47:47.520
it a millimeter away.

47:47.520 --> 47:48.880
You'll get two points.

47:48.880 --> 47:51.320
You do it on your back.

47:51.320 --> 47:54.240
You can get three inches, and they won't feel two points.

47:54.240 --> 48:00.120
There is a maturational aspect of this, I think, which is involved in control of the

48:00.120 --> 48:06.520
pencil to do the thing, which is different from how wonderfully language apparatus is.

48:06.520 --> 48:09.320
Remember, the first year is nonverbal.

48:09.320 --> 48:11.680
Infancy means without speech.

48:11.680 --> 48:18.440
Then all of a sudden, between one year and three years of age, you become a one-word person

48:18.440 --> 48:25.840
to a well-articulated seven-word sentence phrase, representational stuff.

48:25.840 --> 48:32.680
The language apparatus is much more maturationally available to you than the representational

48:32.680 --> 48:33.680
thing.

48:33.680 --> 48:40.480
The only people who's, the only creatures on Earth who not only speak and think in language

48:40.480 --> 48:44.080
of that sort, but also write and represent themselves.

48:44.080 --> 48:56.440
I also think that there is a brilliant kind of symbolism in these early drawings that

48:56.440 --> 49:07.200
they are somehow, the child shows what's important in a way that Picasso famously said, it's

49:07.200 --> 49:09.280
taken me years to learn to draw like a child.

49:09.280 --> 49:20.080
There's a certain way in which the child gets down when the child is left to do it.

49:20.080 --> 49:23.920
Why did you say in use of a wonderful phrase, trained up for it?

49:23.920 --> 49:27.640
Well, the child isn't trained up for it, but when the child is left, the child has a way

49:27.640 --> 49:33.080
of getting down in the simplest way what really matters.

49:33.080 --> 49:34.680
That drawing was amazing.

49:34.680 --> 49:37.920
That drawing was the scooter bicycle thing.

49:37.920 --> 49:47.320
So I think that's also a part of it, that there's a certain beautiful simplicity with

49:47.320 --> 49:53.640
all the little details that we learn sort of shunted aside because they're not what matters.

49:53.640 --> 49:58.040
I wanted to tell you that, Ellen, as you were talking, I was looking for one example that

49:58.040 --> 50:04.640
I don't have here, but you mentioned how as a child is drawing things happen, change,

50:04.640 --> 50:06.240
and influences what happens next.

50:06.240 --> 50:09.280
I wanted to give you one example of that.

50:09.280 --> 50:13.680
One I wanted wasn't here, but I'll find it is, again, in asking the child to do a house

50:13.680 --> 50:17.920
tree person, a family drawing, we get to see picture picture picture.

50:17.920 --> 50:21.920
So here, for instance, this is one girl, happens to be seven.

50:21.920 --> 50:22.920
So she does a person.

50:22.920 --> 50:24.240
We know she can draw a person.

50:24.240 --> 50:28.000
It's not maybe very clear, but there's a stick person with a fancy head.

50:28.000 --> 50:31.000
Then another person, next to it, she can draw the person.

50:31.000 --> 50:32.720
She can draw a tree.

50:32.720 --> 50:34.680
She can draw a house.

50:34.680 --> 50:38.280
And then I asked her to draw a picture of a family doing something, and she does that

50:38.280 --> 50:40.560
thing up there on the right hand side.

50:40.560 --> 50:42.440
Do you see it?

50:42.440 --> 50:45.560
So, and very careful and detailed.

50:45.560 --> 50:49.640
And I said, tell me about this.

50:49.640 --> 51:00.160
And she says, the two light purple balls, which are at six and nine o'clock, and there

51:00.160 --> 51:02.720
are two dark purple balls at twelve and three o'clock.

51:02.720 --> 51:05.160
I think you can see the colors and differences.

51:05.160 --> 51:09.520
And then she says, the vertical yellow line connects the light and dark balls, that's

51:09.520 --> 51:11.480
at twelve and six.

51:11.480 --> 51:16.240
And then there's this line drawing horizontally between three and nine o'clock.

51:16.240 --> 51:18.240
She's going through this very carefully.

51:18.240 --> 51:23.520
And then she explains that these lines keep the balls apart because if they get too close,

51:23.520 --> 51:26.920
they explode.

51:26.920 --> 51:30.080
So here you have something else that's crept into.

51:30.080 --> 51:34.520
This girl can draw figures, and this is her kinetic family drawing, and the answer is,

51:34.520 --> 51:38.840
this is her kinetic family drawing.

51:38.840 --> 51:44.480
Family therapists talk about trying in families, this is a drawing of it.

51:44.480 --> 51:48.880
But another more profound example was a boy who drew very tiny figures.

51:48.880 --> 51:55.200
A boy, really tiny in the middle of a big page, only pencil, no color.

51:55.200 --> 51:59.200
And then he does a tiny tree in a tiny house, and then I say, no, and not draw a picture

51:59.200 --> 52:01.760
of a family doing something.

52:01.760 --> 52:09.320
And he looks, if I'm you, he's looking at me during the pencil, it's pointed and poisoned

52:09.320 --> 52:12.240
the air, and then he goes like this.

52:12.240 --> 52:17.360
Looking up in the corner over there, and my student from the university is sitting there

52:17.360 --> 52:19.960
ready to take notes, and nothing's happening.

52:19.960 --> 52:23.720
And I ask, do you understand what I mean by a family doing something?

52:23.720 --> 52:26.200
And the student says, do you know what a family is?

52:26.200 --> 52:30.200
And he goes, and he goes like this.

52:30.200 --> 52:34.360
So this boy says something in what he doesn't do.

52:34.360 --> 52:37.000
That is something about the family for him.

52:37.000 --> 52:40.920
Let's say, interferes with his, what he can do, which is to draw figures.

52:40.920 --> 52:43.360
So this is so important.

52:43.360 --> 52:44.920
That's what I'm interested in.

52:44.920 --> 52:46.080
I'm very interested in that.

52:46.080 --> 52:52.040
I'm interested in that, in the child taking time, not doing something.

52:52.040 --> 52:55.960
And also, what does the child draw first?

52:55.960 --> 52:58.000
So you have a family.

52:58.000 --> 53:01.160
Which figure does the child draw first?

53:01.160 --> 53:02.680
Does the child draw the father first?

53:02.680 --> 53:05.160
Does the child draw himself first?

53:05.160 --> 53:07.720
And where are these figures placed?

53:07.720 --> 53:09.920
And which ones are close?

53:09.920 --> 53:13.080
Which ones are far away from each other?

53:13.080 --> 53:18.600
But I really think it's dangerous, or not dangerous, that's too strong a word.

53:18.600 --> 53:25.920
But I think it's maybe irresponsible to put too much, I think you said this, to put too

53:25.920 --> 53:32.800
much weight on any thing of this kind.

53:32.800 --> 53:40.720
It's only useful when it's in the context, in a much larger context.

53:40.720 --> 53:48.520
And what I think we really can't do is to treat a child's drawing as we would treat

53:48.520 --> 53:53.960
a complex work of our, you know, a statue by Bernini or a painting by Rembrandt.

53:53.960 --> 53:59.480
A child's drawing is something else.

53:59.480 --> 54:03.600
It's something which is spontaneous.

54:03.600 --> 54:06.600
It does have psychological content.

54:06.600 --> 54:09.800
Indubitably, it does.

54:09.800 --> 54:20.680
But I think that it needs a great deal of context before it can be said to have any kind of

54:20.680 --> 54:21.680
definitive.

54:21.680 --> 54:25.000
Does that make sense to you?

54:25.000 --> 54:29.440
Why one does a study as I did over three years with these families?

54:29.440 --> 54:34.440
But that's also why you ask them to draw something and then you use it as a vehicle

54:34.440 --> 54:40.440
to then probe ideas that you might have asked directly because you know if you ask it directly,

54:40.440 --> 54:46.240
you're not going to get the same rich experience that you got or the kind of creative aspects

54:46.240 --> 54:49.480
that we're talking about.

54:49.480 --> 54:53.000
Maybe it's, let me show you two images.

54:53.000 --> 54:55.000
Push ahead.

54:55.000 --> 54:56.840
More.

